<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="sampling" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Sampling</title>

  <p>
    The third portion of this book introduces statistical inference. This chapter is about
    <term>sampling</term><idx><h>sampling</h></idx>. Sampling involves drawing repeated random
    samples from a population. In <xref ref="sampling-activity"/>, we illustrate sampling by
    working with samples of white and red balls and the proportion of red balls in these samples.
    In <xref ref="sampling-framework"/>, we present a theoretical framework and define what is
    the sampling distribution. We introduce one of the fundamental theoretical results in
    Statistics: the <term>Central Limit Theorem</term><idx><h>Central Limit Theorem</h></idx>
    in <xref ref="central-limit-theorem"/>. In <xref ref="sampling-activity-mean"/>, we present
    a second sampling activity, this time working with samples of chocolate-covered almonds and
    the average weight of these samples. In <xref ref="sampling-other-scenarios"/>, we present
    the sampling distribution in other scenarios. The concepts behind <em>sampling</em> form the
    basis of inferential methods, in particular confidence intervals and hypothesis tests; methods
    that are studied in <xref ref="confidence-intervals"/> and <xref ref="hypothesis-testing"/>.
  </p>

  <!-- Needed packages -->
  <subsection xml:id="sampling-packages">
    <title>Needed packages</title>
    <p>
      We now load all the packages needed for this chapter (this assumes you've already installed
      them). The <c>moderndive</c> and <c>infer</c> packages contain functions and data frames
      used in this chapter.
    </p>
    <program language="r">
      <input>
library(tidyverse)
library(moderndive)
library(infer)
      </input>
    </program>
  </subsection>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="sampling-activity">
    <title>First activity: red balls</title>

    <subsection xml:id="population-proportion">
      <title>The proportion of red balls in the bowl</title>

      <p>
        Imagine you have a large bowl filled with red and white balls, as shown in
        <xref ref="sampling-exercise-1"/>. The bowl contains a mix of colors and you want to
        know what proportion of the balls are red.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="sampling-exercise-1">
        <caption>A bowl with red and white balls.</caption>
        <image source="images/sampling/balls/sampling_bowl_1.jpg" width="80%">
          <description>A large bowl containing a mixture of red and white balls.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        The bowl is represented by the <c>bowl</c> data frame in the <c>moderndive</c> package.
        Let's explore it:
      </p>

      <console prompt="&gt; ">
        <input>
bowl
        </input>
        <output>
# A tibble: 2,400 × 2
   ball_ID color
     &lt;int&gt; &lt;chr&gt;
 1       1 white
 2       2 white
 3       3 white
 4       4 red  
 5       5 white
 6       6 white
 7       7 red  
 8       8 white
 9       9 red  
10      10 white
# ℹ 2,390 more rows
        </output>
      </console>

      <p>
        To compute the proportion of red balls, we can first create an indicator variable that
        is <c>TRUE</c> if a ball is red and <c>FALSE</c> otherwise:
      </p>

      <console prompt="&gt; ">
        <input>
bowl |&gt;
  mutate(is_red = (color == "red"))
        </input>
        <output>
# A tibble: 2,400 × 3
   ball_ID color is_red
     &lt;int&gt; &lt;chr&gt; &lt;lgl&gt; 
 1       1 white FALSE 
 2       2 white FALSE 
 3       3 white FALSE 
 4       4 red   TRUE  
 5       5 white FALSE 
 6       6 white FALSE 
 7       7 red   TRUE  
 8       8 white FALSE 
 9       9 red   TRUE  
10      10 white FALSE 
# ℹ 2,390 more rows
        </output>
      </console>

      <p>
        Next, we can count the number of red balls by summing the indicator variable (since
        <c>TRUE</c> counts as 1 and <c>FALSE</c> as 0):
      </p>

      <console prompt="&gt; ">
        <input>
bowl |&gt;
  mutate(is_red = (color == "red")) |&gt;
  summarize(num_red = sum(is_red))
        </input>
        <output>
# A tibble: 1 × 1
  num_red
    &lt;int&gt;
1     900
        </output>
      </console>

      <p>
        The <c>sum()</c> function effectively counts red balls. There are 375 red balls in the
        bowl. We can compute the proportion by using <c>mean()</c> instead of <c>sum()</c>:
      </p>

      <console prompt="&gt; ">
        <input>
bowl |&gt;
  mutate(is_red = (color == "red")) |&gt;
  summarize(prop_red = mean(is_red))
        </input>
        <output>
# A tibble: 1 × 1
  prop_red
     &lt;dbl&gt;
1    0.375
        </output>
      </console>

      <p>
        Using <c>mean()</c> on a <c>TRUE</c>/<c>FALSE</c> variable gives the proportion directly
        because it computes the fraction of <c>TRUE</c> values. We can write this more concisely as:
      </p>

      <console prompt="&gt; ">
        <input>
bowl |&gt;
  summarize(prop_red = mean(color == "red"))
        </input>
        <output>
# A tibble: 1 × 1
  prop_red
     &lt;dbl&gt;
1    0.375
        </output>
      </console>

      <p>
        The proportion of red balls is 375/2400 = 0.375, or approximately 37.5% of all balls in
        the bowl.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sampling-manual">
      <title>Manual sampling</title>

      <p>
        In practice, it is often impractical or impossible to count every element in a large
        population. For example, if the bowl contained millions of balls, exhaustively counting
        all of them would be prohibitive. Instead, we use a physical sampling approach: we insert
        a shovel into the bowl, draw out a sample, and use it to estimate the population
        proportion.
      </p>

      <subsubsection xml:id="sampling-one-sample">
        <title>One sample</title>

        <p>
          We insert a shovel into the bowl to collect a sample of balls, as shown in
          <xref ref="sampling-exercise-2a"/> and <xref ref="sampling-exercise-2b"/>.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="sampling-exercise-2a">
          <caption>Inserting a shovel into the bowl.</caption>
          <image source="images/sampling/balls/sampling_bowl_2.jpg" width="80%">
            <description>A shovel being inserted into a bowl of red and white balls.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <figure xml:id="sampling-exercise-2b">
          <caption>Taking a sample of 50 balls from the bowl.</caption>
          <image source="images/sampling/balls/sampling_bowl_3_cropped.jpg" width="80%">
            <description>A shovel holding a sample of 50 balls extracted from the bowl.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          The shovel has a 5-row by 10-column grid, so it scoops exactly <m>5 \times 10 = 50</m>
          balls at a time. In one particular sample, 17 of the 50 balls were red, giving a sample
          proportion of <m>17/50 = 0.34</m>. This is somewhat close to the true population
          proportion of 0.375, but not exactly equal. The difference arises from
          <term>sampling variation</term><idx><h>sampling</h><h>variation</h></idx>.
        </p>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="sampling-thirty-three">
        <title>Thirty-three samples</title>

        <p>
          We can repeat this process: return the balls to the bowl, mix them up, and draw another
          sample. By repeating this many times we can study how the sample proportion varies from
          sample to sample. Thirty-three students performed this activity, each taking one sample
          of 50 balls.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="sampling-exercise-3b">
          <caption>Repeating the sampling activity.</caption>
          <sidebyside>
            <image source="images/sampling/balls/tactile_2_a.jpg" width="30%">
              <description>Students taking samples from the bowl.</description>
            </image>
            <image source="images/sampling/balls/tactile_2_b.jpg" width="30%">
              <description>Students recording the number of red balls in their sample.</description>
            </image>
            <image source="images/sampling/balls/tactile_2_c.jpg" width="30%">
              <description>Students completing their sampling worksheet.</description>
            </image>
          </sidebyside>
        </figure>

        <figure xml:id="sampling-exercise-3c">
          <caption>Students drawing a histogram of sample proportions.</caption>
          <image source="images/sampling/balls/tactile_3_a.jpg" width="80%">
            <description>Students drawing a histogram of their sample proportions on a whiteboard.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <figure xml:id="sampling-exercise-3d">
          <caption>Hand-drawn histogram of 10 sample proportions.</caption>
          <image source="images/sampling/balls/tactile_3_c-2e.png" width="80%">
            <description>A hand-drawn histogram showing the distribution of 10 sample proportions of red balls.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          The results of all 33 students' samples are stored in the <c>tactile_prop_red</c> data
          frame in the <c>moderndive</c> package:
        </p>

        <console prompt="&gt; ">
          <input>
tactile_prop_red
          </input>
          <output>
# A tibble: 33 × 4
   group            replicate red_balls prop_red
   &lt;chr&gt;                &lt;int&gt;     &lt;int&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
 1 Ilyas, Yohan             1        21     0.42
 2 Morgan, Terrance         2        17     0.34
 3 Martin, Thomas           3        21     0.42
 4 Clark, Frank             4        21     0.42
 5 Riddhi, Karina           5        18     0.36
 6 Andrew, Tyler            6        19     0.38
 7 Julia                    7        19     0.38
 8 Rachel, Lauren           8        11     0.22
 9 Daniel, Caroline         9        15     0.3 
10 Josh, Maeve             10        17     0.34
# ℹ 23 more rows
          </output>
        </console>

        <p>
          Let's visualize the distribution of sample proportions with a histogram:
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
ggplot(tactile_prop_red, aes(x = prop_red)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.05, boundary = 0.4, color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Proportion of red balls in each sample",
       title = "Histogram of 33 proportions")
          </input>
        </program>

        <figure xml:id="samplingdistribution-tactile">
          <caption>The distribution of sample proportions based on 33 random samples of size 50.</caption>
          <image source="images/07-sampling/samplingdistribution-tactile-1.png" width="80%">
            <description>A histogram showing the distribution of 33 sample proportions of red balls, each from a sample of size 50.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          Notice that no two students got exactly the same proportion. This is
          <term>sampling variation</term><idx><h>sampling</h><h>variation</h></idx>: different
          random samples from the same population produce different sample statistics. The
          distribution of these sample proportions is called the
          <term>sampling distribution</term><idx><h>sampling distribution</h></idx> of the sample
          proportion.
        </p>

        <p>
          Let's introduce some key vocabulary:
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Sampling</term><idx><h>sampling</h></idx>: The act of drawing a subset
                (sample) from a larger group (population).
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Sampling with replacement</term><idx><h>sampling</h><h>with replacement</h></idx>:
                Each selected item is returned to the population before the next draw, so the same
                item could theoretically be selected more than once.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Random samples</term><idx><h>random sample</h></idx>: Samples drawn such
                that every member of the population has an equal chance of being selected.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Sampling variation</term><idx><h>sampling</h><h>variation</h></idx>:
                The natural variability in a sample statistic from sample to sample.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>

        <exercises>
          <exercise xml:id="lc7-1">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Why is it important to mix the balls in the bowl before we take a new sample?
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                To randomize selection and reduce dependence or bias between samples.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>

          <exercise xml:id="lc7-2">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Why is it that students did not all have the same sample proportion of red balls?
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                Sampling variation. Different random samples from the same population yield
                different statistics.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>
        </exercises>
      </subsubsection>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sampling-simulation">
      <title>Virtual sampling</title>

      <p>
        Instead of physically taking samples from a bowl, we can use a computer to simulate the
        process. This extends the tactile sampling activity to simulations that are faster,
        scalable, and reproducible. We use the <c>rep_slice_sample()</c> function from the
        <c>moderndive</c> package.
      </p>

      <subsubsection xml:id="virtual-one-sample">
        <title>One virtual sample</title>

        <p>
          Let's take one virtual sample of 50 balls from the bowl:
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
virtual_shovel &lt;- bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 50)
virtual_shovel
          </input>
        </program>

        <p>
          Now compute the proportion of red balls in this virtual sample:
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
virtual_shovel |&gt;
  summarize(prop_red = mean(color == "red"))
          </input>
        </program>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="virtual-thirty-three">
        <title>Thirty-three virtual samples</title>

        <p>
          We can simulate 33 samples at once by specifying <c>reps = 33</c>:
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
virtual_samples &lt;- bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 50, reps = 33)
virtual_samples
          </input>
        </program>

        <p>
          Now we compute the sample proportion for each of the 33 replications using
          <c>group_by()</c> and <c>summarize()</c>:
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
virtual_prop_red &lt;- virtual_samples |&gt;
  group_by(replicate) |&gt;
  summarize(prop_red = mean(color == "red"))
virtual_prop_red
          </input>
        </program>

        <p>
          We can also do this in one pipeline:
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
virtual_prop_red &lt;- bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 50, reps = 33) |&gt;
  summarize(prop_red = mean(color == "red"))
virtual_prop_red
          </input>
        </program>

        <p>
          Visualizing the distribution of the 33 virtual sample proportions:
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
ggplot(virtual_prop_red, aes(x = prop_red)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.05, boundary = 0.4, color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Sample proportion",
       title = "Histogram of 33 sample proportions")
          </input>
        </program>

        <figure xml:id="samplingdistribution-virtual">
          <caption>The distribution of 33 proportions based on 33 virtual samples of size 50.</caption>
          <image source="images/07-sampling/samplingdistribution-virtual-1.png" width="80%">
            <description>A histogram showing the distribution of 33 virtual sample proportions of red balls.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <figure xml:id="tactile-vs-virtual">
          <caption>The sampling distribution of the sample proportion and sampling variation: showing a histogram for virtual sample proportions (left) and another histogram for tactile sample proportions (right).</caption>
          <image source="images/07-sampling/tactile-vs-virtual-1.png" width="80%">
            <description>Side-by-side histograms comparing virtual and tactile sample proportions of red balls.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <exercises>
          <exercise xml:id="lc7-3">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Why couldn't we study the effects of sampling variation when we used the virtual
                shovel only once?
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                One sample shows only one outcome. Many samples are needed to observe variability
                and form a sampling distribution.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>
        </exercises>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="virtual-thousand">
        <title>One thousand virtual samples</title>

        <p>
          To better understand the shape of the sampling distribution, let's take 1000 virtual
          samples instead of just 33:
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
virtual_prop_red &lt;- bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 50, reps = 1000) |&gt;
  summarize(prop_red = mean(color == "red"))
virtual_prop_red
          </input>
        </program>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
ggplot(virtual_prop_red, aes(x = prop_red)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.04, boundary = 0.4, color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Sample proportion", title = "Histogram of 1000 sample proportions")
          </input>
        </program>

        <figure xml:id="samplingdistribution-virtual-1000">
          <caption>The distribution of 1000 proportions based on 1000 random samples of size 50.</caption>
          <image source="images/07-sampling/samplingdistribution-virtual-1000-1.png" width="80%">
            <description>A histogram showing the distribution of 1000 virtual sample proportions of red balls, exhibiting a symmetric, bell-shaped distribution.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          With 1000 samples, the distribution is clearly symmetric and bell-shaped, closely
          approximated by a normal distribution. This is the sampling distribution of the sample
          proportion for <m>n = 50</m>.
        </p>

        <exercises>
          <exercise xml:id="lc7-4">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Why did we not take 1000 samples of 50 balls by hand?
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                It is impractical and time consuming. Simulation is fast, scalable, and
                reproducible.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>

          <exercise xml:id="lc7-5">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Looking at the histogram, would you say that sampling 50 balls where 30% of them
                were red is likely or not? What about 10%?
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                30% is plausible though less common. 10% is very unlikely.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>
        </exercises>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="virtual-different-sizes">
        <title>Different sample sizes</title>

        <p>
          What happens to the sampling distribution when we change the sample size? Instead of
          always using a shovel that scoops 50 balls, consider using shovels of three different
          sizes, as shown in <xref ref="three-shovels"/>.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="three-shovels">
          <caption>Three shovels to extract three different sample sizes.</caption>
          <image source="images/sampling/balls/three_shovels.png" width="80%">
            <description>Three shovels of different sizes used to extract samples of 25, 50, and 100 balls respectively.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          The following code computes 1000 sample proportions for each of three sample sizes
          (25, 50, and 100) and displays the resulting histograms:
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
# Segment 1: sample size = 25 ------------------------------
# 1.a) Compute sample proportions for 1000 samples, each sample of size 25
virtual_prop_red_25 &lt;- bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 25, reps = 1000) |&gt;
  summarize(prop_red = mean(color == "red"))

# 1.b) Plot a histogram to represent the distribution of the sample proportions
ggplot(virtual_prop_red_25, aes(x = prop_red)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.05, boundary = 0.4, color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Proportion of 25 balls that were red", title = "25")


# Segment 2: sample size = 50 ------------------------------
# 2.a) Compute sample proportions for 1000 samples, each sample of size 50
virtual_prop_red_50 &lt;- bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 50, reps = 1000) |&gt;
  summarize(prop_red = mean(color == "red"))

# 2.b) Plot a histogram to represent the distribution of the sample proportions
ggplot(virtual_prop_red_50, aes(x = prop_red)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.05, boundary = 0.4, color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Proportion of 50 balls that were red", title = "50")


# Segment 3: sample size = 100 ------------------------------
# 3.a) Compute sample proportions for 1000 samples, each sample of size 100
virtual_prop_red_100 &lt;- bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 100, reps = 1000) |&gt;
  summarize(prop_red = mean(color == "red"))

# 3.b) Plot a histogram to represent the distribution of the sample proportions
ggplot(virtual_prop_red_100, aes(x = prop_red)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.05, boundary = 0.4, color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Proportion of 100 balls that were red", title = "100")
          </input>
        </program>

        <figure xml:id="comparing-sampling-distributions">
          <caption>Histograms of sample proportions for different sample sizes.</caption>
          <image source="images/07-sampling/comparing-sampling-distributions-1.png" width="80%">
            <description>Three histograms side by side showing the distribution of sample proportions for sample sizes of 25, 50, and 100 balls respectively.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          Comparing the three histograms in <xref ref="comparing-sampling-distributions"/>, we
          observe three important features:
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                All three histograms are centered around the same value, slightly below 0.4,
                close to the true population proportion of 0.375.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                All three histograms are somewhat bell-shaped.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                As the sample size increases from 25 to 50 to 100, the sampling variation
                decreases: the histograms become narrower. Larger samples produce sample
                proportions that are more consistently close to the true population proportion.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>

        <exercises>
          <exercise xml:id="lc7-6">
            <statement>
              <p>
                As shown in <xref ref="comparing-sampling-distributions"/>, what can you say
                about the center of the histograms?
                <ol label="A">
                  <li><p>Smaller sample sizes lead to a more concentrated center.</p></li>
                  <li><p>Larger sample sizes lead to a smaller center value.</p></li>
                  <li><p>The center of each histogram seems to be about the same, regardless of the sample size.</p></li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <term>C.</term> The center of each histogram seems to be about the same,
                regardless of the sample size.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>

          <exercise xml:id="lc7-7">
            <statement>
              <p>
                As the sample size increases, the histogram gets narrower. What happens with the
                sample proportions?
                <ol label="A">
                  <li><p>They vary less.</p></li>
                  <li><p>They vary by the same amount.</p></li>
                  <li><p>They vary more.</p></li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <term>A.</term> They vary less.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>

          <exercise xml:id="lc7-8">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Why do we use random sampling when constructing sampling distributions?
                <ol label="A">
                  <li><p>To always get the same sample.</p></li>
                  <li><p>To minimize bias and make inferences about the population.</p></li>
                  <li><p>To make the process easier.</p></li>
                  <li><p>To reduce the number of samples needed.</p></li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <term>B.</term> To minimize bias and make inferences about the population.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>

          <exercise xml:id="lc7-9">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Why is it important to construct a histogram of sample means or proportions in a
                simulation study?
                <ol label="A">
                  <li><p>To visualize the distribution and assess normality or other patterns.</p></li>
                  <li><p>To increase accuracy.</p></li>
                  <li><p>To ensure all sample means are exactly the same.</p></li>
                  <li><p>To remove outliers.</p></li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <term>A.</term> To visualize the distribution and assess normality or other
                patterns.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>
        </exercises>
      </subsubsection>
    </subsection>
  </section>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="sampling-framework">
    <title>Sampling framework</title>

    <p>
      In <xref ref="sampling-activity"/>, we gained intuition about sampling by working with
      the bowl of red and white balls. Now we introduce the formal statistical definitions and
      notation that underlie what we observed.
    </p>

    <subsection xml:id="terminology-and-notation">
      <title>Population, sample, and the sampling distribution</title>

      <p>
        The following key terms formalize the concepts we encountered in the bowl activity:
      </p>

      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Population</term><idx><h>population</h></idx> or
              <term>study population</term><idx><h>study population</h></idx>: The collection of
              all individuals or cases of interest. In the bowl activity, the population is all
              2400 balls in the bowl.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Sample</term><idx><h>sample</h></idx>: A subset of the population that we
              actually observe. In the bowl activity, each sample of 50 balls drawn by the shovel
              is a sample.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Sampling</term><idx><h>sampling</h></idx>: The act of collecting a sample from
              a population.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Simple random sampling</term><idx><h>simple random sampling</h></idx>: A
              sampling procedure in which each member of the population has the same chance of
              being selected. Samples collected this way are called
              <term>random samples</term><idx><h>random sample</h></idx>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Population parameter</term><idx><h>population parameter</h></idx> (or simply
              <term>parameter</term><idx><h>parameter</h></idx>): A numerical summary of the
              population. In the bowl activity, the population parameter is the true proportion
              of red balls, <m>p = 0.375</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Sample statistic</term><idx><h>sample statistic</h></idx> (or simply
              <term>statistic</term><idx><h>statistic</h></idx>): A numerical summary computed
              from a sample. In the bowl activity, the sample statistic is the sample proportion
              of red balls, <m>\widehat{p}</m>. For example, with 17 red balls in a sample of
              50, <m>\widehat{p} = 0.34</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Distribution</term><idx><h>distribution</h></idx>: The set of all possible
              values a variable can take and how often each value occurs.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Sampling distribution of the sample proportion</term><idx><h>sampling distribution</h><h>of the sample proportion</h></idx>:
              The distribution of all sample proportions obtained from each possible random
              sample of a given size drawn from the population. In the bowl activity, this is
              the distribution shown in <xref ref="comparing-sampling-distributions"/> across
              repeated samples.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>

      <p>
        It is important to distinguish between two different distributions. The
        <em>distribution of a sample</em> describes the values within a single sample (e.g., the
        colors of the 50 balls in one particular scoop). The
        <em>sampling distribution of the sample proportion</em> describes how the sample
        proportion varies across many repeated samples, as illustrated in
        <xref ref="comparing-sampling-distributions"/>. The sampling distribution is what allows
        us to make statements about the reliability of our estimates.
      </p>

      <p>
        From our exploration in <xref ref="sampling-simulation"/>, we observed three key
        characteristics of the sampling distribution:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Center</em>: The average of all sample proportions is approximately equal to the
              true population proportion <m>p</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Sampling variation and sample size effect</em>: The spread of the sampling
              distribution decreases as the sample size increases. Larger samples produce less
              variable sample proportions.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Shape</em>: For sufficiently large sample sizes, the sampling distribution is
              approximately bell-shaped (normal).
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="lc7-10">
          <statement>
            <p>
              In the case of our bowl activity, what is the population parameter? Do we know its
              value? How can we know its value exactly?
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              The population parameter is the true proportion of red balls, <m>p</m>. We can know
              it exactly by counting all balls and computing the proportion in the full population.
              In this case, <m>p = 375/2400 = 0.375</m>.
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc7-11">
          <statement>
            <p>
              How did we ensure that the samples collected with the shovel were random?
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              By mixing the bowl between samples and sampling with replacement so each ball has
              equal chance on each draw.
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>
    </subsection>
  </section>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="central-limit-theorem">
    <title>The Central Limit Theorem</title>

    <p>
      One of the most fascinating results in all of statistics is this: when we repeatedly draw
      random samples from <em>any</em> population and compute the sample mean (or sample
      proportion), the resulting histogram of those sample means will be approximately bell-shaped
      with very specific and predictable features, regardless of the shape of the population's
      distribution. This result is known as the
      <term>Central Limit Theorem</term><idx><h>Central Limit Theorem</h></idx> (CLT).
    </p>

    <subsection xml:id="random-variables-proportion">
      <title>Random variables</title>

      <p>
        To understand the CLT, we first introduce the concept of a
        <term>random variable</term><idx><h>random variable</h></idx>. Consider the following
        experiment, called a <term>Bernoulli trial</term><idx><h>Bernoulli trial</h></idx>:
        randomly select one ball from the bowl (with replacement) and record a 1 if the ball is
        red and a 0 if it is white. Each such trial has a random outcome because we don't know in
        advance which ball will be selected.
      </p>

      <p>
        We use capital letters to denote random variables. Let <m>X_1</m> represent the outcome of
        the first trial: after we draw the ball and observe its color, we have a realized value,
        either <m>X_1 = 1</m> (red) or <m>X_1 = 0</m> (white). Similarly, <m>X_2</m> is the
        outcome of the second trial, and so on.
      </p>

      <p>
        If we select 25 balls (25 trials), we have <m>X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_{25}</m>. The sample
        mean of these 25 Bernoulli trials is:
        <me>
          \overline{X} = \frac{X_1 + X_2 + \dots + X_{25}}{25}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        After drawing our 25 balls, suppose 10 were red. Then
        <m>\overline{X} = 10/25 = 0.4</m>. In the context of Bernoulli trials where outcomes are
        0 or 1, the sample mean equals the sample proportion:
        <m>\overline{X} = \widehat{p}</m>. After observing the outcome, the realized value of the
        sample mean is a specific number.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sampling-dist-rv">
      <title>The sampling distribution using random variables</title>

      <p>
        If we take another random sample of 25 balls, we get a different set of values
        <m>X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_{25}</m> and therefore a different value of
        <m>\overline{X}</m>. The set of all possible values of <m>\overline{X}</m> and the
        probability of each constitutes the sampling distribution of the sample proportion. This
        distribution is influenced by the proportion of red and white balls in the bowl.
      </p>

      <p>
        We study three key characteristics of the distribution of <m>\overline{X}</m>:
        <ol>
          <li><p>The center of the distribution of <m>\overline{X}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>The effect of sampling variation on the distribution of <m>\overline{X}</m> and the effect of sample size.</p></li>
          <li><p>The shape of the distribution of <m>\overline{X}</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="expected-value">
      <title>The center of the distribution: the expected value</title>

      <p>
        The center of the sampling distribution of <m>\overline{X}</m> is its average value over
        infinitely many repeated samples. This average is called the
        <term>expected value</term><idx><h>expected value</h></idx> of <m>\overline{X}</m>,
        denoted <m>E(\overline{X})</m>. Based on probability theory:
        <me>
          E(\overline{X}) = p = 0.375
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        This means that the sampling distribution of the sample proportion is centered at the
        true population proportion <m>p</m>. We can verify this empirically using our simulated
        data. <xref ref="comparing-sampling-distributions-3"/> shows the three sampling
        distributions with a vertical line at <m>p = 0.375</m>.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="comparing-sampling-distributions-3">
        <caption>Three sampling distributions with population proportion <m>p</m> marked by a vertical line.</caption>
        <image source="images/07-sampling/comparing-sampling-distributions-3-1.png" width="80%">
          <description>Three histograms for sample sizes 25, 50, and 100, each with a vertical line at p equals 0.375 marking the population proportion.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
virtual_prop_red_25
virtual_prop_red_25 |&gt;
  summarize(E_Xbar_25 = mean(prop_red))
        </input>
      </program>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
virtual_prop_red_50 |&gt;
  summarize(E_Xbar_50 = mean(prop_red))
virtual_prop_red_100 |&gt;
  summarize(E_Xbar_100 = mean(prop_red))
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>
        In each case, the average of the 1000 sample proportions is approximately equal to the
        population proportion 0.375. The simulation gives us an approximation of the theoretical
        result, not the exact result, because we only used 1000 samples rather than all possible
        samples.
      </p>

      <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="lc7-12">
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is the expected value of the sample mean in the context of sampling
              distributions?
              <ol label="A">
                <li><p>The observed value from a single sample.</p></li>
                <li><p>The population mean.</p></li>
                <li><p>The median of the sample.</p></li>
                <li><p>The midpoint of the range of sample means.</p></li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              <term>B.</term> The population mean.
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sampling-variation">
      <title>Sampling variation: standard deviation and standard error</title>

      <p>
        From <xref ref="comparing-sampling-distributions"/>, we observed that as the sample size
        increases, the variation in the sampling distribution decreases. We now quantify this
        variation using the standard deviation.
      </p>

      <subsubsection xml:id="standard-deviation">
        <title>The standard deviation</title>

        <p>
          Recall the standard deviation from our earlier work. As a quick review, consider four
          values: <m>y_1 = 3</m>, <m>y_2 = -1</m>, <m>y_3 = 5</m>, <m>y_4 = 9</m>. Their
          average is:
          <me>
            \bar{y} = \frac{1}{4}\sum_{i=1}^{4} y_i = \frac{3 + (-1) + 5 + 9}{4} = 4
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          The symbol <m>\sum_{i=1}^{4}</m> (read <q>sum from <m>i = 1</m> to <m>4</m></q>)
          means we add the quantities that follow for each value of <m>i</m> from 1 to 4: in
          other words, <m>y_1 + y_2 + y_3 + y_4</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          The standard deviation measures the typical deviation of each value from the mean. We
          construct it in steps: find the deviations from the mean, square them, average them
          (to get the variance), and take the square root:
          <md>
            <mrow>
              SD \amp= \sqrt{\frac{1}{4}\sum_{i=1}^{4}(y_i - \bar{y})^2}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp= \sqrt{\frac{(3-4)^2 + (-1-4)^2 + (5-4)^2 + (9-4)^2}{4}}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp= \sqrt{\frac{1 + 25 + 1 + 25}{4}}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp= \sqrt{\frac{52}{4}} = \sqrt{13} \approx 3.61
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Returning to the bowl, we can compute the population standard deviation of the
          <m>0/1</m> indicator of <q>red ball</q>:
        </p>

        <console prompt="&gt; ">
          <input>
bowl |&gt;
  mutate(is_red = color == "red") |&gt;
  summarize(p = mean(is_red), st_dev = sd(is_red))
          </input>
          <output>
# A tibble: 1 × 2
      p st_dev
  &lt;dbl&gt;  &lt;dbl&gt;
1 0.375  0.484
          </output>
        </console>

        <p>
          The result is <m>p = 0.375</m> and <m>SD \approx 0.484</m>.<fn>The <c>sd()</c>
          function actually calculates the <em>sample</em> standard deviation, which divides by
          <m>n - 1</m> instead of <m>n</m>. The difference is noticeable for small numbers but
          almost irrelevant for large numbers like the 2400 balls in our bowl.</fn> This means
          that when randomly selecting many balls, we expect a proportion of about 0.375 red
          balls, give or take about 0.484.
        </p>

        <p>
          For a Bernoulli random variable with probability <m>p</m>, there is an elegant
          closed-form formula: <m>SD = \sqrt{p(1-p)}</m>. We can verify this:
        </p>

        <console prompt="&gt; ">
          <input>
p &lt;- 0.375
sqrt(p * (1 - p))
          </input>
          <output>
[1] 0.4841229
          </output>
        </console>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="standard-error">
        <title>The standard error</title>

        <p>
          While the standard deviation describes the variability of individual ball selections,
          we are actually interested in the variability of <em>sample proportions</em>. The
          standard deviation of the sampling distribution has a special name: the
          <term>standard error</term><idx><h>standard error</h></idx>. It is important to
          remember that <q>all standard errors are standard deviations but not all standard
          deviations are standard errors.</q> A standard error specifically refers to the
          standard deviation of a sample statistic.
        </p>

        <p>
          We can compute the standard error empirically. Let's take 10,000 samples of size
          <m>n = 100</m> and compute the standard deviation of the resulting sample proportions:
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 100, replace = TRUE, reps = 10000) |&gt;
  summarize(prop_red = mean(color == "red")) |&gt;
  summarize(p = mean(prop_red), SE_Xbar = sd(prop_red))
          </input>
        </program>

        <p>
          Observe that <c>p</c> is the estimated expected value and <c>SE_Xbar</c> is the
          estimated standard error based on the simulation of taking sample proportions for
          random samples of size <m>n = 100</m>. Compare this value with the standard deviation
          for the entire bowl, discovered earlier. It is one-tenth the size! This is not a
          coincidence: the standard error of <m>\overline{X}</m> is equal to the standard
          deviation of the population (the bowl) divided by the square root of the sample size.
        </p>

        <p>
          There is also a theoretical formula for the standard error of the sample proportion:
          <me>
            SE(\overline{X}) = \sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}
          </me>
          For <m>p = 0.375</m> and <m>n = 100</m>:
          <me>
            SE(\overline{X}) = \sqrt{\frac{0.375 \times 0.625}{100}} \approx 0.0484
          </me>
        </p>

        <console prompt="&gt; ">
          <input>
p &lt;- 0.375
sqrt(p * (1 - p) / 100)
          </input>
          <output>
[1] 0.04841229
          </output>
        </console>

        <p>
          We can repeat this for <m>n = 25</m> and <m>n = 50</m> using our simulated data:
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
virtual_prop_red_25 |&gt;
  summarize(SE_Xbar_25 = sd(prop_red))
virtual_prop_red_50 |&gt;
  summarize(SE_Xbar_50 = sd(prop_red))
          </input>
        </program>

        <console prompt="&gt; ">
          <input>
sqrt(p * (1 - p) / 25)
sqrt(p * (1 - p) / 50)
          </input>
          <output>
[1] 0.06846532
          </output>
        </console>

        <p>
          In each case, the empirical standard deviation of the 1000 simulated sample proportions
          closely matches the theoretical standard error from the formula. The simulations are
          used to check that in fact the results achieved agree with the theory. Observe also
          that the theoretical results are constructed based on the knowledge of the population
          proportion, <m>p</m>; by contrast, the simulations produce samples based on the
          population of interest but produce results only based on information found from samples
          and sample proportions. For more details, see
          <url href="http://onlinestatbook.com/2/sampling_distributions/samp_dist_p.html">
            Online Statistics Education: A Multimedia Course of Study
          </url>.
        </p>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="shape-sampling-proportion">
        <title>The sampling distribution of the sample proportion</title>

        <p>
          The third key characteristic is shape. From our histograms in
          <xref ref="comparing-sampling-distributions"/>, the sampling distributions appeared
          bell-shaped. We can confirm this by overlaying a normal distribution curve on each
          histogram, as shown in <xref ref="sample-proportion-25-with-normal-pdf"/>,
          <xref ref="sample-proportion-50-with-normal-pdf"/>, and
          <xref ref="sample-proportion-100-with-normal-pdf"/>.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="sample-proportion-25-with-normal-pdf">
          <caption>Histogram of the distribution of the sample proportion and the normal curve (<m>n = 25</m>).</caption>
          <image source="images/07-sampling/sample-proportion-25-with-normal-pdf-1.png" width="80%">
            <description>A histogram of 1000 sample proportions for sample size 25 with an overlaid normal distribution curve.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <figure xml:id="sample-proportion-50-with-normal-pdf">
          <caption>Histogram of the distribution of the sample proportion and the normal curve (<m>n = 50</m>).</caption>
          <image source="images/07-sampling/sample-proportion-50-with-normal-pdf-1.png" width="80%">
            <description>A histogram of 1000 sample proportions for sample size 50 with an overlaid normal distribution curve.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <figure xml:id="sample-proportion-100-with-normal-pdf">
          <caption>Histogram of the sampling distribution of the sample proportion and the normal curve (<m>n = 100</m>).</caption>
          <image source="images/07-sampling/sample-proportion-100-with-normal-pdf-1.png" width="80%">
            <description>A histogram of 1000 sample proportions for sample size 100 with an overlaid normal distribution curve.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          In each figure, the red normal curve (with mean <m>p = 0.375</m> and standard deviation
          <m>\sqrt{p(1-p)/n}</m>) fits the histogram remarkably well. This is a manifestation of
          the <term>Central Limit Theorem</term><idx><h>Central Limit Theorem</h></idx>: as the
          sample size <m>n \to \infty</m>, the distribution of <m>\overline{X}</m> converges to
          a normal distribution. Remarkably, this approximation works well even for fairly small
          sample sizes.
        </p>

        <exercises>
          <exercise xml:id="lc7-13">
            <statement>
              <p>
                What is the role of the Central Limit Theorem in statistical inference?
                <ol label="A">
                  <li><p>It provides a formula for the standard deviation of any distribution.</p></li>
                  <li><p>It says the sampling distribution of the sample mean approaches a normal distribution regardless of the population distribution, as the sample size becomes large.</p></li>
                  <li><p>It determines the actual mean from a single sample.</p></li>
                  <li><p>It only applies to normally distributed populations.</p></li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <term>B.</term> It says the sampling distribution of the sample mean approaches
                a normal distribution regardless of the population distribution, as the sample
                size becomes large.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>

          <exercise xml:id="lc7-14">
            <statement>
              <p>
                What does <q>sampling variation</q> refer to?
                <ol label="A">
                  <li><p>Variability in the population itself.</p></li>
                  <li><p>Differences in sample statistics due to random sampling.</p></li>
                  <li><p>Changes in the population parameter over time.</p></li>
                  <li><p>Variation caused by errors in data collection.</p></li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <term>B.</term> Differences in sample statistics due to random sampling.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>
        </exercises>
      </subsubsection>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="clt-summary">
      <title>Summary</title>

      <p>
        We can summarize the key results of this section in three points:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The mean of all sample proportions equals the population proportion <m>p</m>. Sample
              proportions are unbiased estimators of the population proportion.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The standard error is inversely proportional to <m>\sqrt{n}</m>:
              <m>SE(\overline{X}) = \sqrt{p(1-p)/n}</m>. As the sample size increases, the
              sample proportions cluster more tightly around the population proportion on average.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              As long as random samples are large enough, the sampling distribution of the sample
              proportion is approximately normal, regardless of the distribution of the population.
              This is the Central Limit Theorem.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <p>
        For a concise visual explanation of the CLT, watch this short video (3 min 38 sec) by
        Shuyi Chiou, Casey Dunn, and Pathikrit Bhattacharyya:
        <url href="https://youtu.be/jvoxEYmQHNM">Central Limit Theorem video</url>.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="CLT-video-preview">
        <caption>Preview of the Central Limit Theorem video.</caption>
        <image source="images/copyright/CLT_video_preview.png" width="80%">
          <description>A screenshot preview of a video explaining the Central Limit Theorem.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </subsection>
  </section>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="sampling-activity-mean">
    <title>Second activity: chocolate-covered almonds</title>

    <p>
      In <xref ref="sampling-activity"/> and <xref ref="central-limit-theorem"/>, we studied
      sampling distributions for the sample proportion, a special case of the sample mean for
      binary (0/1) data. We now extend these results to the general case of the sample mean
      for continuous data, using chocolate-covered almonds as our population.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="almonds-bowl-photo">
      <caption>A bowl of chocolate-covered almonds.</caption>
      <image source="images/sampling/almonds/v2_side_almonds.jpg" width="80%">
        <description>A large bowl filled with chocolate-covered almonds.</description>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <subsection xml:id="population-mean">
      <title>The population mean weight of almonds in the bowl</title>

      <p>
        The <c>almonds_bowl</c> data frame in the <c>moderndive</c> package contains the weights
        (in grams) of all 5000 almonds in a bowl:
      </p>

      <console prompt="&gt; ">
        <input>
almonds_bowl
        </input>
        <output>
# A tibble: 5,000 × 2
      ID weight
   &lt;int&gt;  &lt;dbl&gt;
 1     1    3.8
 2     2    4.2
 3     3    3.2
 4     4    3.1
 5     5    4.1
 6     6    3.9
 7     7    3.4
 8     8    4.2
 9     9    3.5
10    10    3.4
# ℹ 4,990 more rows
        </output>
      </console>

      <console prompt="&gt; ">
        <input>
almonds_bowl |&gt;
  summarize(mean_weight = mean(weight),
            sd_weight = sd(weight),
            length = n())
        </input>
        <output>
# A tibble: 1 × 3
  mean_weight sd_weight length
        &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;  &lt;int&gt;
1        3.64     0.392   5000
        </output>
      </console>

      <p>
        The bowl contains 5000 almonds with a population mean weight of
        <m>\mu = 3.64</m> grams and a population standard deviation of
        <m>\sigma = 0.392</m> grams.<fn>The <c>sd()</c> function uses <m>n - 1</m> in the
        denominator, but for 5000 observations the difference from using <m>n</m> is not relevant
        for practical purposes.</fn>
      </p>

      <p>
        More precisely, using Greek letters for population parameters:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Population mean</term><idx><h>population mean</h></idx>:
              <m>\mu = \frac{1}{5000}\sum_{i=1}^{5000} x_i = 3.64</m> grams.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Population standard deviation</term><idx><h>population standard deviation</h></idx>:
              <m>\sigma = \sqrt{\frac{1}{5000}\sum_{i=1}^{5000}(x_i - \mu)^2} = 0.392</m> grams.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>

      <p>
        We can visualize the distribution of all 5000 almond weights:
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
ggplot(almonds_bowl, aes(x = weight)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1, color = "white")
        </input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="almonds-bowl-histogram">
        <caption>Distribution of weights for the entire bowl of almonds.</caption>
        <image source="images/07-sampling/almonds-bowl-histogram-1.png" width="80%">
          <description>A histogram showing the distribution of weights for all 5000 almonds in the bowl.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        The weights range from about 2.6 to 4.6 grams, with the most common weights falling
        between 3.6 and 4.0 grams. Notice that the distribution is not symmetric — it has a
        slight left skew with a longer left tail. This is an important point: the CLT says that
        the sampling distribution of the sample mean will be approximately normal even when the
        population distribution itself is not normal.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="resampling-tactile-bowl">
      <title>Manual sampling and sample means</title>

      <p>
        Just as we physically scooped balls from the bowl in <xref ref="sampling-manual"/>, we
        can physically scoop almonds. <xref ref="one-almond"/> shows one almond on a scale, and
        <xref ref="twenty-five-almonds"/> shows a random sample of 25 almonds weighed together.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="one-almond">
        <caption>One almond on a scale.</caption>
        <image source="images/sampling/almonds/one-almond.png" width="80%">
          <description>A single chocolate-covered almond on a digital scale.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure xml:id="twenty-five-almonds">
        <caption>A random sample of 25 almonds on a scale.</caption>
        <image source="images/sampling/almonds/twenty-five-almonds.png" width="80%">
          <description>A random sample of 25 chocolate-covered almonds on a digital scale showing the total weight.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        The <c>almonds_sample</c> data frame contains the weights of a particular random sample
        of 25 almonds:
      </p>

      <console prompt="&gt; ">
        <input>
almonds_sample
        </input>
        <output>
# A tibble: 25 × 3
# Groups:   replicate [1]
   replicate    ID weight
       &lt;int&gt; &lt;int&gt;  &lt;dbl&gt;
 1         1  4645    3  
 2         1  3629    3.9
 3         1  4796    4  
 4         1  2669    3.8
 5         1  3488    4.3
 6         1   105    4.1
 7         1  1762    3.6
 8         1  1035    4.2
 9         1  4880    3.2
10         1   398    4  
# ℹ 15 more rows
        </output>
      </console>

      <p>
        The total weight of the 25 almonds in this sample was 88.6 grams, giving a sample mean
        of <m>88.6/25 = 3.544</m> grams. The <c>almonds_sample</c> data frame has columns for
        the replicate number, the almond ID, and the weight. Let's visualize the distribution of
        weights in this sample:
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
ggplot(almonds_sample, aes(x = weight)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1, color = "white")
        </input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="almonds-sample-histogram">
        <caption>Distribution of weight for a sample of 25 almonds.</caption>
        <image source="images/07-sampling/almonds-sample-histogram-1.png" width="80%">
          <description>A histogram showing the distribution of weights for a sample of 25 almonds.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <console prompt="&gt; ">
        <input>
almonds_sample |&gt; summarize(sample_mean_weight = mean(weight))
        </input>
        <output>
# A tibble: 1 × 2
  replicate sample_mean_weight
      &lt;int&gt;              &lt;dbl&gt;
1         1               3.67
        </output>
      </console>

      <p>
        The sample mean is not too far from the true population mean of 3.64 grams. The
        difference is due to sampling variation.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="virtual-samples-mean-bowl">
      <title>Virtual sampling</title>

      <p>
        We now use virtual sampling to take 1000 random samples of 25 almonds and compute the
        sample mean weight for each:
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
virtual_samples_almonds &lt;- almonds_bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 25, reps = 1000)
virtual_samples_almonds
        </input>
      </program>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
virtual_mean_weight &lt;- virtual_samples_almonds |&gt;
  summarize(mean_weight = mean(weight))
virtual_mean_weight
        </input>
      </program>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
ggplot(virtual_mean_weight, aes(x = mean_weight)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.04, boundary = 3.5, color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Sample mean", title = "Histogram of 1000 sample means")
        </input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="sampling-mean-virtual-1000">
        <caption>The distribution of 1000 means based on 1000 random samples of size 25.</caption>
        <image source="images/07-sampling/sampling-mean-virtual-1000-1.png" width="80%">
          <description>A histogram showing the distribution of 1000 sample mean weights for random samples of 25 almonds.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        The sample means range from below 3.4 to above 3.85 grams, with most values falling
        between 3.5 and 3.8 grams. The distribution is almost symmetric and bell-shaped, with
        a slightly longer left tail — mirroring the slight left skew of the population
        distribution, though much less pronounced.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sampling-dist-mean">
      <title>The sampling distribution of the sample mean</title>

      <p>
        As with sample proportions, we study the sampling distribution of the sample mean by
        examining three key characteristics: its center, its spread (and the effect of sample
        size), and its shape.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="random-variable-sample-mean">
      <title>Random variables</title>

      <p>
        Instead of Bernoulli trials recording 0 or 1, here each trial records the weight of a
        randomly selected almond. We select one almond, record its weight, return it to the bowl,
        and repeat. We have 25 trials total.
      </p>

      <p>
        Let <m>X_1</m> be the weight of the first randomly selected almond — a random variable.
        Similarly, <m>X_2, X_3, \ldots, X_{25}</m> are the weights of the subsequent almonds.
        After drawing all 25 almonds, we have realized values <m>x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_{25}</m>
        (e.g., 3.0 g, 3.9 g, 4.0 g, and so on).
      </p>

      <p>
        The sample mean is:
        <me>
          \overline{X} = \frac{X_1 + X_2 + \dots + X_{25}}{25}
        </me>
        Note that sample proportions are a special case of sample means: when the trials are
        Bernoulli 0/1, the sample mean equals the sample proportion.
      </p>

      <console prompt="&gt; ">
        <input>
almonds_sample
        </input>
        <output>
# A tibble: 25 × 3
# Groups:   replicate [1]
   replicate    ID weight
       &lt;int&gt; &lt;int&gt;  &lt;dbl&gt;
 1         1  4645    3  
 2         1  3629    3.9
 3         1  4796    4  
 4         1  2669    3.8
 5         1  3488    4.3
 6         1   105    4.1
 7         1  1762    3.6
 8         1  1035    4.2
 9         1  4880    3.2
10         1   398    4  
# ℹ 15 more rows
        </output>
      </console>

      <p>
        For our observed sample, the first three almonds weighed approximately 3.0 g, 3.9 g,
        and 4.0 g. The sample mean is:
        <me>
          \overline{X} = \frac{3.0 + 3.9 + 4.0 + \dots + 3.3 + 4.4 + 3.6}{25}
                       = \frac{91.8}{25} = 3.67
        </me>
      </p>

      <console prompt="&gt; ">
        <input>
almonds_sample |&gt;
  summarize(sample_mean_weight = mean(weight))
        </input>
        <output>
# A tibble: 1 × 2
  replicate sample_mean_weight
      &lt;int&gt;              &lt;dbl&gt;
1         1               3.67
        </output>
      </console>

      <p>
        After observing the sample, the realized value of the sample mean is
        <m>\overline{X} = 3.67</m> grams.
      </p>

      <p>
        To study all three key characteristics of the distribution of <m>\overline{X}</m>, we
        take 1000 samples each of sizes 25, 50, and 100 and compute the histograms of sample
        means:
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
# Segment 1: sample size = 25 ------------------------------
# 1.a) Calculating the 1000 sample means, each from random samples of size 25
virtual_mean_weight_25 &lt;- almonds_bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 25, reps = 1000) |&gt;
  summarize(mean_weight = mean(weight), n = n())

# 1.b) Plot distribution via a histogram
ggplot(virtual_mean_weight_25, aes(x = mean_weight)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.02, boundary = 3.6, color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Sample mean weights for random samples of 25 almonds", title = "25")

# Segment 2: sample size = 50 ------------------------------
# 2.a) Calculating the 1000 sample means, each from random samples of size 50
virtual_mean_weight_50 &lt;- almonds_bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 50, reps = 1000) |&gt;
  summarize(mean_weight = mean(weight), n = n())

# 2.b) Plot distribution via a histogram
ggplot(virtual_mean_weight_50, aes(x = mean_weight)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.02, boundary = 3.6, color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Sample mean weights for random samples of 50 almonds", title = "50")

# Segment 3: sample size = 100 ------------------------------
# 3.a) Calculating the 1000 sample means, each from random samples of size 100
virtual_mean_weight_100 &lt;- almonds_bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 100, reps = 1000) |&gt;
  summarize(mean_weight = mean(weight), n = n())

# 3.b) Plot distribution via a histogram
ggplot(virtual_mean_weight_100, aes(x = mean_weight)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.02, boundary = 3.6, color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Sample mean weights for random samples of 100 almonds", title = "100")
        </input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="comparing-sampling-distributions-means">
        <caption>Comparing histograms of sample means when using different sample sizes.</caption>
        <image source="images/07-sampling/comparing-sampling-distributions-means-1.png" width="80%">
          <description>Three histograms side by side showing the distribution of sample mean weights for sample sizes of 25, 50, and 100 almonds respectively.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        All three histograms are bell-shaped and centered around the same value, approximately
        equal to the population mean <m>\mu = 3.64</m> grams. Sampling variation decreases as
        the sample size increases.
      </p>

      <p>
        We can compute the population parameters and compare them to the simulation results:
      </p>

      <console prompt="&gt; ">
        <input>
almonds_bowl |&gt;
  summarize(mu = mean(weight), sigma = sd(weight))
        </input>
        <output>
# A tibble: 1 × 2
     mu sigma
  &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt;
1  3.64 0.392
        </output>
      </console>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
# n = 25
virtual_mean_weight_25 |&gt;
  summarize(E_Xbar_25 = mean(mean_weight), sd = sd(mean_weight))

# n = 50
virtual_mean_weight_50 |&gt;
  summarize(E_Xbar_50 = mean(mean_weight), sd = sd(mean_weight))

# n = 100
virtual_mean_weight_100 |&gt;
  summarize(E_Xbar_100 = mean(mean_weight), sd = sd(mean_weight))
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>
        From these results, comparing across sample sizes:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The expected value is approximately <m>3.64</m> or <m>3.65</m> grams
              <m>\approx \mu = 3.64</m> in all cases. Sample means are unbiased estimators of
              the population mean.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The standard error decreases as <m>n</m> increases. For <m>n = 100</m>:
              <m>SE \approx \sigma/10</m>. For <m>n = 25</m>: <m>SE \approx \sigma/5</m>. For
              <m>n = 50</m>: <m>SE \approx \sigma/7</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <p>
        This leads to the formula for the standard error of the sample mean:
        <me>
          SE_{\overline{X}} = \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}
        </me>
        As the sample size <m>n</m> increases, the standard error decreases proportionally to
        <m>1/\sqrt{n}</m>.
      </p>

      <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="lc7-15">
          <statement>
            <p>
              How does increasing the sample size affect the standard error of the sample mean?
              <ol label="A">
                <li><p>It increases the standard error.</p></li>
                <li><p>It decreases the standard error.</p></li>
                <li><p>It has no effect on the standard error.</p></li>
                <li><p>It only affects the standard deviation, not the standard error.</p></li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              <term>B.</term> It decreases the standard error.
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="CLT-mean">
      <title>The Central Limit Theorem revisited</title>

      <p>
        The histograms in <xref ref="comparing-sampling-distributions-means"/> are bell-shaped,
        suggesting a normal approximation. We can confirm this by overlaying normal distribution
        curves, as shown in <xref ref="sample-mean-25-with-normal"/> and
        <xref ref="sample-mean-100-with-normal"/>.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="sample-mean-25-with-normal">
        <caption>The distribution of the sample mean (<m>n = 25</m>).</caption>
        <image source="images/07-sampling/sample-mean-25-with-normal-1.png" width="80%">
          <description>A histogram of 1000 sample mean weights for sample size 25 with an overlaid normal distribution curve.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure xml:id="sample-mean-100-with-normal">
        <caption>The distribution of the sample mean (<m>n = 100</m>).</caption>
        <image source="images/07-sampling/sample-mean-100-with-normal-1.png" width="80%">
          <description>A histogram of 1000 sample mean weights for sample size 100 with an overlaid normal distribution curve.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        The CLT applies here just as it did for proportions: when the sample size is large
        enough, the distribution of <m>\overline{X}</m> is approximately normal with mean
        <m>\mu</m> and standard deviation <m>\sigma/\sqrt{n}</m>:
        <me>
          \overline{X} \sim \mathrm{Normal}\!\left(\mu,\, \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)
        </me>
        This is remarkable because the population distribution of almond weights is not
        symmetric (it has a left skew), yet the sampling distribution of the sample mean is
        approximately normal for sufficiently large <m>n</m>.
      </p>

      <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="lc7-16">
          <statement>
            <p>
              For each of the following cases, explain whether the sampling distribution of the
              sample mean approximates a normal distribution:
              <ol label="a">
                <li><p>When the population distribution is normal.</p></li>
                <li><p>When the sample size is very large.</p></li>
                <li><p>When the sample size is sufficiently large, regardless of the population distribution.</p></li>
                <li><p>When the population distribution is uniform.</p></li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              <ol label="a">
                <li><p>Yes, for any sample size <m>n</m>, because the mean of normal random variables is itself normal.</p></li>
                <li><p>Yes, by the CLT.</p></li>
                <li><p>Yes, by the CLT.</p></li>
                <li><p>Approximately normal if <m>n</m> is large, but not necessarily for small <m>n</m>.</p></li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>
    </subsection>
  </section>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="sampling-other-scenarios">
    <title>The sampling distribution in other scenarios</title>

    <p>
      In <xref ref="sampling-activity"/>, <xref ref="central-limit-theorem"/>, and
      <xref ref="sampling-activity-mean"/>, we studied the expected value, standard error, and
      shape for sample proportions and sample means. The same principles apply to other sample
      statistics as well. In this section, we consider the sampling distribution of statistics
      based on two independent samples.
    </p>

    <subsection xml:id="sampling-two-samples">
      <title>Sampling distribution for two samples</title>

      <p>
        Many studies compare parameters across two populations. For example, we might ask
        whether the average weight of almonds from one supplier differs from that of another,
        or whether one treatment produces better outcomes than another. In such cases, we take
        independent random samples from each population and compare sample statistics.
      </p>

      <subsubsection xml:id="diff-sample-means">
        <title>Difference in sample means</title>

        <p>
          Suppose we compare the average weight of chocolate-covered almonds (population 1)
          against the average weight of coffee beans (population 2). The sample statistic of
          interest is the difference in sample means:
          <m>\overline{X}_1 - \overline{X}_2</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Let population 1 have mean <m>\mu_1</m> and standard deviation <m>\sigma_1</m>, and
          let population 2 have mean <m>\mu_2</m> and standard deviation <m>\sigma_2</m>. We
          draw independent random samples of sizes <m>n_1</m> and <m>n_2</m>. Then by the CLT:
          <me>
            \overline{X}_1 - \overline{X}_2
            \sim \mathrm{Normal}\!\left(
              \mu_1 - \mu_2,\;
              \sqrt{\frac{\sigma_1^2}{n_1} + \frac{\sigma_2^2}{n_2}}
            \right)
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          Notice that when computing the standard error of the difference, we <em>add</em> the
          variances rather than subtract them. This is because both samples contribute uncertainty
          independently: adding or subtracting two random quantities always increases the total
          uncertainty.
        </p>

        <exercises>
          <exercise xml:id="lc7-17">
            <statement>
              <p>
                In the context of comparing two samples, why do we add variances instead of
                subtracting when finding the standard error of a difference?
                <ol label="A">
                  <li><p>Because variances cancel out.</p></li>
                  <li><p>Because adding reflects the total uncertainty contributed by both independent samples.</p></li>
                  <li><p>Because subtracting would give negative results.</p></li>
                  <li><p>Because variances are not related to standard errors.</p></li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <term>B.</term> Because adding variances reflects the total uncertainty
                contributed by both independent samples.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>
        </exercises>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="diff-sample-proportions">
        <title>Difference in sample proportions</title>

        <p>
          We can also compare two sample proportions. Suppose we want to compare the proportion
          of red balls in the bowl (population 1) with the proportion of almonds heavier than
          3.8 grams in the almond bowl (population 2). We take a sample of <m>n_1 = 50</m> balls
          and a sample of <m>n_2 = 60</m> almonds.
        </p>

        <p>
          The process is:
          <ol>
            <li><p>Draw a random sample from population 1 and compute <m>\widehat{p}_1</m> = proportion of red balls.</p></li>
            <li><p>Draw an independent random sample from population 2 and compute <m>\widehat{p}_2</m> = proportion of almonds with weight <m>&gt; 3.8</m> g.</p></li>
            <li><p>Compute the difference <m>\widehat{p}_1 - \widehat{p}_2</m>.</p></li>
          </ol>
        </p>

        <p>
          We can simulate this:
        </p>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
virtual_prop_red &lt;- bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 50, reps = 1000) |&gt;
  summarize(prop_red = mean(color == "red"))
virtual_prop_almond &lt;- almonds_bowl |&gt;
  rep_slice_sample(n = 60, reps = 1000) |&gt;
  summarize(prop_almond = mean(weight &gt; 3.8))
prop_joined &lt;- virtual_prop_red |&gt;
  inner_join(virtual_prop_almond, by = "replicate") |&gt;
  mutate(prop_diff = prop_red - prop_almond)
          </input>
        </program>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
prop_joined
          </input>
        </program>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
ggplot(prop_joined, aes(x = prop_diff)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.04, boundary = 0, color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Difference in sample proportions",
       title = "Histogram of 1000 differences in sample proportions")
          </input>
        </program>

        <figure xml:id="samplingdistribution-virtual-diff-1000">
          <caption>The distribution of 1000 differences in sample proportions.</caption>
          <image source="images/07-sampling/samplingdistribution-virtual-diff-1000-1.png" width="80%">
            <description>A histogram showing the distribution of 1000 differences in sample proportions between red ball proportions and heavy almond proportions.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          The histogram is also bell-shaped, centered around a negative value of approximately
          <m>-0.05</m>, reflecting the fact that the proportion of almonds heavier than 3.8
          grams is somewhat higher than the proportion of red balls.
        </p>

        <p>
          For <m>\overline{X}_1</m> (proportion of red balls, <m>n_1 = 50</m>) and
          <m>\overline{X}_2</m> (proportion of almonds <m>&gt; 3.8</m> g, <m>n_2 = 60</m>),
          the CLT gives:
          <me>
            \overline{X}_1 - \overline{X}_2
            \sim \mathrm{Normal}\!\left(
              p_1 - p_2,\;
              \sqrt{\frac{p_1(1-p_1)}{n_1} + \frac{p_2(1-p_2)}{n_2}}
            \right)
          </me>
        </p>

        <exercises>
          <exercise xml:id="lc7-18">
            <statement>
              <p>
                What is the sampling distribution of the difference in sample proportions
                expected to look like if both samples are large enough?
                <ol label="A">
                  <li><p>Uniform.</p></li>
                  <li><p>Bell-shaped, approximating a normal distribution.</p></li>
                  <li><p>Bimodal.</p></li>
                  <li><p>Skewed to the right.</p></li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <term>B.</term> Bell-shaped, approximating a normal distribution.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </exercise>
        </exercises>
      </subsubsection>
    </subsection>
  </section>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="sampling-final-remarks">
    <title>Summary and final remarks</title>

    <subsection xml:id="sampling-summary-scenarios">
      <title>Summary of scenarios</title>

      <p>
        The scenarios studied in this chapter — sample proportion, sample mean, and difference
        in proportions or means — are not the only cases where sampling distributions arise. For
        example, the slope coefficient in linear regression also has a sampling distribution,
        which we study in <xref ref="inference-for-regression"/>. A summary table of sampling
        scenarios, including the sample statistic, the population parameter, the expected value,
        and the standard error formula, provides a useful reference for all the cases studied in
        this chapter.
      </p>

      <p>
        Across all cases, the three key results remain the same:
        <ol>
          <li><p>The expected value of the sample statistic equals the population parameter.</p></li>
          <li><p>The standard error decreases as the sample size increases.</p></li>
          <li><p>For large enough samples, the sampling distribution is approximately normal (CLT).</p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sampling-additional-resources">
      <title>Additional resources</title>

      <p>
        Solutions to all Learning Checks in this chapter can be found in the Appendices at
        <url href="https://moderndive.com/v2/appendixa">moderndive.com/v2/appendixa</url>.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sampling-whats-next">
      <title>What's to come?</title>

      <p>
        The upcoming <xref ref="confidence-intervals"/> on confidence intervals will delve deeper
        into statistical inference. We will explore how to construct and interpret confidence
        intervals, what a confidence level means, the limitations of confidence intervals, and
        practical applications. The concepts of sampling distributions and standard errors
        developed in this chapter form the theoretical foundation for all of that work.
      </p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

</chapter>
